         <PROCEDURE>
            <DIRECTIVE_2009_81_EC>
               <PT_NEGOTIATED_WITHOUT_PUBLICATION>
                  <D_ACCORDANCE_ARTICLE>
                     <D_TECHNICAL/>
                  </D_ACCORDANCE_ARTICLE>
                  <D_JUSTIFICATION>
                     <P>Project THAUMA Phase 2 — Reactivation and in-service support for the M3 Bridging System — New Contract.</P>
                     <P>Operational Infrastructure (OI), part of the UK Ministry of Defence, intends to place a new single Contract (OIP/0044) with the Original Equipment Manufacturer (OEM) and Design Authority (DA), General Dynamics European Land Systems — Germany (GDELS — G). The Contract shall be for a period of up to 8 years to reactivate up to 13 M3 Bridges and to provide in-service support for the M3 fleet of 27 Rigs.</P>
                     <P>It is considered that this contract can be placed with GDELS-G using the negotiated procedure without prior publication of a Contract notice under Regulation 16 (1)(a)(ii) of the Defence and Security Public Contracts Regulations 2011 (Article 28(1)(e) of Directive 2009/81/EC). Reactivation and in-service support of the M3 capability can only be placed with GDELS-G for the following reasons:</P>
                     <P>1. GDELS-G is the Original Equipment Manufacturer (OEM) and the current Design Authority (DA) for the M3 equipment. An alternate supplier would not have access to necessary knowhow in order to have a sufficient technical understanding of the equipment to be able to understand and underwrite the health and safety implications of any modifications.</P>
                     <P>2. In order to conduct Level 4 repairs the contractor will require a considerable number of jigs and specialist tools for the M3 system. These jigs and tools are bespoke to the M3 system and have been manufactured as required by the OEM over the lifetime of the M3 equipment. The Authority do not own or have user rights to any information pertaining to these jigs and specialist tools. Any redesign of such jigs and tools by an alternative supplier is considered to increase the technical risk associated with the equipment to an unacceptable level.</P>
                  </D_JUSTIFICATION>
               </PT_NEGOTIATED_WITHOUT_PUBLICATION>
            </DIRECTIVE_2009_81_EC>
